AGI -&nbsp;
<span> In a neoclassical building in Athens, in the oldest street of one of the oldest neighborhoods in the Western world, residents gathered last week with many concerns. </span
&nbsp;
Among the points on the agenda were noise pollution, traffic congestion and other modern problems, but there was one that was welcomed with immediate relief: Haris Doukas, mayor of the city, had decided to set up a task force to save Plaka, the old neighborhood in the heart of the historic center of the capital. >
&nbsp;
“It was the news that we all wanted to hear,” says Lydia Carras, president of the Society for the Environment and the Cultural Heritage Ellet, in which locals often gather residents. “Finally measures are taken.”
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
For Carras, who founded the association for the protection of the heritage 50 years ago with the deceased Anglo-Greek husband Costas, it is a battle reminiscent of old struggles. More than four decades after the “quarter of the gods” survived the invasion of nightclubs > and bar with terrace, its discovery by investors and global real estate companies, is again representing an existential threat. On the wave of the tourist boom, entire buildings have fallen prey to the short-term rental industry of Airbnb.
&nbsp;
The few proximity shops that have resisted are, like residents, on the edge of extinction.&nbsp; “The Plaka must be protected because it is so unique”, says Carras. “Thanks to special laws it was saved many years ago. The reality now is that residents leave and not only because the laws are violated; the crowd, noise, chaos have made their lives unbearable.”
&nbsp;
The visitors, he said, do not want to experience “skenographs without life”, but inhabited areas that feel authentic and real. “This is a small neighborhood. It was built for residents, not for what we see today.”
&nbsp;
<h2> In 2025, 10 million francs of visitors </h2>
The projections on arrivals of tourists are to say little exciting, to prove that Athens is no longer a pit-stop > for travellers traveling to the islands. But the forecasts, in front of record peaks, are also full of risks.
&nbsp;
This year it is expected that 10 million visitors, > two million more than 2024, will descend into the capital, many of which for the city breaks that made it so popular. If only one part will head towards Plaka, there will be an “tolerant pressure” on its labyrinth network of alleys and roads.
&nbsp;
“From 35 million tourists that Greece is preparing to welcome, 10 million, almost equal to the entire Greek population, will visit Athens,” he says. “For the first time we will be the first Greek destination, but it is not sustainable. The Plaka, in particular, is oversaturated. You can’t move on.”
&nbsp;
A recent study on the “capacity of load”, commissioned by the Municipality and drafted by the University of Piraeus, urged the authorities to take immediate steps if Athens wants to avoid becoming victim of its own success.
“There is no day to lose. We must act if we do not want to become next Barcelona, > and that is why the task force, with the support of the municipal police, will have at its disposal all the services", said Doukas, professor of energy policy before the center-left party Pasok applied it.
&nbsp;

